- Understanding the valuation processes for different categories of financial assets and liabilities, including relevant controls;
- Evaluating and testing the controls, including computer system-based controls;
- Confirming the existence, rights and obligations, valuation, and completeness of financial assets and liabilities through direct communication with the entities involved;
- Verifying prices obtained from independent sources if market quotes are used;
- If valuation techniques incorporate observable market data, assessing whether the valuation models are appropriate and the assumptions reasonable, and verifying the parameters from independent sources; and
- If valuation techniques rely on unobservable inputs, assessing the appropriateness of the valuation models and the reasonableness of the assumptions and parameters involved.

- Obtaining and reviewing valuation reports for properties directly held by the Group or through associates or joint ventures, and verifying that the fair values are derived based on the relevant valuation reports;
- Evaluating the independence and qualifications of the valuers; and
- Assessing whether the valuation methods are appropriate, and whether the assumptions and parameters involved are reasonable.

- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement of the financial statements due to fraud or error; design and perform audit procedures responsive to those risks; and obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence to draw reasonable conclusions. Because fraud may involve collusion, falsification, deliberate omissions, false representations, or circumventing internal controls, the risk of not detecting a material misstatement due to fraud is higher than for error;
- Understand internal controls relevant to the audit in order to design appropriate procedures. However, I do not express an opinion on the effectiveness of the Group’s internal controls;
- Evaluate whether the accounting policies adopted by the Financial Secretary are appropriate, and whether the accounting estimates and related disclosures are reasonable;
- Conclude whether there is a material uncertainty related to events or conditions that may cast significant doubt on the Group’s ability to continue as a going concern, based on the audit evidence obtained. If I conclude that a material uncertainty exists, I will draw attention in my auditor’s report to the related disclosures in the financial statements. If the disclosures are inadequate, I will issue a modified auditor’s report. My conclusions are based on audit evidence obtained up to the date of my auditor’s report. Future events or conditions may cause the Group to cease to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure, and content of the financial statements, including disclosures, and whether the financial statements represent the underlying transactions and events fairly;
- Obtain sufficient appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of the entities or business activities within the Group to express an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for directing, supervising, and performing the Group audit, and I bear all responsibility for my audit opinion.
